<dl id="n04162h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n04" href="#n04162h">N04 (VI.B.25)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n04all.htm#n04162h"> 162(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> in &frac12; mourning <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n04162h"><li>FW 566.07 </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/lexs.htm#n04162h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/l39s.htm#n04162h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n04162h">MS BL 47485-33</ms> </li><li>JJA 60:261 <a name="sd2" href="../../ff/fdra/sda.htm#sd2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/s/sd2.htm#n04162h">Draft: III&sect;4.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Cowes <mark>in Half Mourning</mark>, / Regatta Change for Dead President. / Postponed Races. [&hellip;]</font>] Cowes is in semi-mourning to-day for President Harding&apos;s funeral, and every token of sympathy with the U.S. is indicated. <br>The big handicap race for yachts exceeding a hundred tons, in which the King&apos;s Britannia is entered, has been postponed until to-morrow, and to-day all yachts lying in the roadstead, including the Victoria and Albert, lowered their flags to half mast. <small> <a name="ES10aug23" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ES10aug23"><cite title="source">Evening Standard</cite></a> (10 August 1923) 16/4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Half-mourning: a period of mourning following the expiry of full mourning, when the black of full mourning clothing is relieved by other colours. </mm> </dd></dl>
